(43, 2, 16, 23, 56, 5, 11, 'my Father’s house an house of merchandise', 'House of Prayer Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the significance of God''s house as a place of worship rather than commerce. John 2:16''s condemnation of merchandise contrasts with Isaiah 56:7''s declaration of the house as a ''house of prayer for all people.''', 'theme', 0.426, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 2, 16, 42, 2, 49, 49, 'my Father’s house', 'Father''s Business and House', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of ''Father''s house'' and ''Father''s business,'' linking Jesus'' mission to the sanctity of the temple. This connection highlights the importance of prioritizing divine purpose over commercial activities.', 'theme', 0.40499999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 2, 16, 61, 2, 14, 15, 'make not my Father’s house an house of merchandise', 'Connection of Commercialism and Sin', 'Both passages emphasize the dangers of covetousness and corruption within sacred spaces. John 2:16 warns against turning the temple into a marketplace, while 2 Peter 2:14-15 describes those who forsake righteousness for unrighteous gain.', 'theme', 0.363, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 2, 16, 28, 12, 7, 8, 'house of merchandise', 'Commercialism and Deceit', 'This connection highlights the theme of commercialism and deceit in both passages. John 2:16 condemns the commercialization of the temple, while Hosea 12:7-8 critiques the dishonest practices of merchants.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 2, 17, 19, 69, 9, 9, 'The zeal of thine house hath eaten me up', 'Connection of Zeal for God''s House', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of zeal for God''s house, illustrating a deep commitment and passion. The phrase ''the zeal of thine house hath eaten me up'' appears verbatim in both texts, linking them thematically.', 'quotation', 0.867, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 2, 17, 19, 119, 139, 139, 'zeal of thine house hath eaten me up', 'Connection of Zeal in Scripture', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of zeal consuming the speaker. In John 2:17, the disciples recall the zeal for God''s house, while Psalms 119:139 expresses personal zeal due to enemies forgetting God''s words.', 'theme', 0.594, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 2, 18, 40, 21, 23, 23, NULL, 'Authority and Signs in the Temple', 'Both passages emphasize questioning Jesus'' authority. In John 2:18, the Jews ask for a sign, while in Matthew 21:23, the chief priests inquire about his authority. This connection highlights the challenge to Jesus'' legitimacy in the temple context.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 2, 18, 41, 8, 11, 11, 'sign shewest thou unto us', 'Demand for Signs', 'Both passages emphasize the request for a sign from Jesus, highlighting the skepticism of religious leaders. This connection illustrates a common theme of questioning Jesus'' authority and miracles.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 2, 18, 41, 11, 27, 28, 'What sign shewest thou unto us', 'Authority and Signs in Scripture', 'Both passages emphasize questioning Jesus'' authority. In John, the Jews ask for a sign, while in Mark, the chief priests inquire about the authority behind his actions.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 2, 18, 43, 6, 30, 30, 'What sign shewest thou', 'Demand for Signs', 'Both passages emphasize a demand for signs from Jesus. The Jews in John 2:18 and the people in John 6:30 both ask, ''What sign shewest thou?'' highlighting a common theme of seeking validation through miraculous works.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 2, 18, 40, 16, 1, 4, 'What sign shewest thou unto us', 'Demand for Signs', 'Both passages emphasize a request for signs from Jesus. In John, the Jews ask, ''What sign shewest thou unto us,'' while in Matthew, the Pharisees and Sadducees seek ''a sign from heaven.'' This connection highlights the theme of skepticism towards Jesus'' authority.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 2, 18, 42, 11, 29, 29, 'What sign shewest thou unto us', 'Seeking Signs in Both Passages', 'Both passages emphasize the demand for signs from Jesus, highlighting a common theme of skepticism among the people. In John, the Jews ask for a sign, while in Luke, Jesus addresses a generation seeking a sign.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 2, 18, 42, 20, 1, 2, 'What sign shewest thou unto us', 'Authority and Signs', 'Both passages emphasize questioning Jesus'' authority. In John, the Jews ask for a sign, while in Luke, the chief priests and scribes inquire about the authority behind his actions.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
